05086nam a22006375i 9781580466875DE-B159720240306010644.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20072007xxk    fo  d z      eng d  a97815804668757 a10.1515/97815804668752doi  a(DE-B1597)674271  a(OCoLC)1097141454  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxkcUK 4aJS5015.D53.B74 2007eb 7aPOL0100002bisacsh04a944/.426033  aNR 8485qBSZ2rvk0(DE-625)rvk/130037:1 aBreen, Michael P., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aLaw, City, and King :bLegal Culture, Municipal Politics, and State Formation in Early Modern Dijon /cMichael P. Breen.31aWoodbridge, Suffolk : bBoydell and Brewer, c[2007] 1bUniversity of Rochester Press, c[2007] 4c©2007  a1 online resource (324 p.) :b9 b/w, 2 line illus.  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aChanging Perspectives on Early Modern Europe ;v600tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tList of Illustrations -- tAcknowledgments -- tAbbreviations -- tIntroduction: Lawyers, Politics, and the State in Early Modern France -- tChapter 1 Lawyers and Municipal Government in Dijon -- tChapter 2 The Avocats and the Politics of Local Privilege (1595–1648) -- tChapter 3 The Collapse of the Municipal Political System (1649–68) -- tChapter 4 From Local Government to Royal Administration (1669–1715) -- tChapter 5 Legal Culture and Political Thought in Early Seventeenth-Century Dijon -- tChapter 6 Custom, Reason, and the Limits of Royal Authority -- tConclusion: Avocats, Politics, and “The Public” in Eighteenth-Century Dijon -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aAn in-depth examination of political activities in early modern France that opens up new perspectives on the local workings of the French state and the experiences of those who participated in it.Law, City, and King provides important new insights into the transformation of political participation and consciousness among urban notables who bridged the gap between local society and the state in early modern France. Breen's detailed research shows how the educated, socially-middling avocats who staffed Dijon's municipality used law, patronage, and the other resources at their disposal to protect the city council's authority and their own participation in local governance. Drawing on juridical and historical authorities, the avocats favored a traditional conception of limited "absolute" monarchy increasingly at odds with royal ideology. Despite their efforts to resist the monarchy's growth, the expansion of royal power under Louis XIV eventually excluded Dijon's avocats from the French state. In opening up new perspectives on the local workings of the French state and the experiences of those who participated in it, Law, City, and King recasts debates about absolutism and early modern state formation. By focusing on the political alienation of notables who had long linked the crown to provincial society, Breen explains why Louis XIV's collaborative absolutism did not endure. At the same time, the book's examination of lawyers' political activities and ideas provides insights into the transformation of French political culturein the decades leading up to the French Revolution. Michael P. Breen is Associate Professor of History and Humanities at Reed College in Portland, Oregon.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aJustice, Administration ofzFrancezDijonxHistoryy17th century. 0aMunicipal governmentzFrancezDijonxHistoryy17th century. 0aPolitical participationzFrancezDijonxHistoryy17th century. 4aEarly Modern History. 4aPolitics & Economics. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / History & Theory.2bisacsh  aDijon.  aFrench politics.  aFrench state formation.